                \n {"practice":"7","code":"SUM-2","subCode":"b) instructions on how to apply approved patches manually and via an automated process;","explanation":"This requirement ensures that product users receive clear, actionable instructions for applying security patches both manually and through automation, reducing vulnerabilities in industrial control systems (ICS).","context":"In ICS environments, timely patch application is critical to mitigate security risks, but manual processes can be error-prone and automation requires careful configuration.","challenges":["Patch compatibility with legacy ICS components: Older systems may not support modern patch formats or automation tools. Example: A PLC from 2010 fails after an automated patch due to firmware incompatibility.","Downtime constraints: Critical ICS operations cannot tolerate frequent restarts. Example: A power plant delays patching due to 24/7 operational requirements.","Testing limitations: Lack of test environments matching production ICS setups. Example: A patch validated in a lab causes communication failures in the live SCADA network.","Vendor coordination: Delays in receiving ICS-specific patch documentation from multiple vendors. Example: A patch for Siemens PLCs lacks instructions for Honeywell HMI integration.","Regulatory compliance: Patches must be validated against industry standards before deployment. Example: A water utility must verify NERC CIP compliance for each patch."],"best_practices":[{"description":"Maintain a patch repository with ICS-specific version control and rollback procedures. Example: Rockwell Automation's FactoryTalk Patch Manager tracks industrial software updates with dependency checks.","url":" https://www.rockwellautomation.com/en-us/products/software/security/factorytalk-patch-manager.html","url_description":"Rockwell's tool for managing patches in industrial environments with version control"},{"description":"Implement change windows with automated patch deploymen